# Plugin Development Rules

## Plugin class structure

```ts
import { UICorePlugin, Events } from '@clappr/core'

export class MyPlugin extends UICorePlugin {
  name = 'my_plugin'       // must be unique; used as PlayerConfig key for options
  static type = 'core'     // 'core' for UICorePlugin, 'container' for ContainerPlugin

  bindEvents() {
    // Use listenTo — auto-cleans up on destroy; never use addEventListener directly
    this.listenTo(this.core, Events.PLAYER_PLAY, this.onPlay)
  }

  private onPlay() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## File layout for a new plugin

```
packages/player/src/plugins/my-feature/
  MyFeature.ts                          # Plugin class + exported settings interface
  __tests__/
    MyFeature.test.ts

assets/my-feature/
  template.ejs                          # EJS template (if UI)
  my-feature.scss                       # Styles (if UI)
```

After creating, export from `packages/player/src/index.plugins.ts`.

## Plugin options

Plugin-specific config is passed via `PlayerConfig` under the plugin's `name` key:
```ts
new Player({ my_plugin: { someOption: true }, sources: [...] })
// accessed inside the plugin as: this.options.my_plugin
```

Export the options interface publicly:
```ts
export interface MyPluginSettings {
  someOption?: boolean
}
```

## Event communication

- Never reference another plugin directly from within a plugin
- Use Clappr's event system for inter-plugin communication
- Use `this.listenTo()` not `this.on()` — `listenTo` tracks the binding and cleans up automatically

## Assets

- Import EJS template: `import myTemplate from '../../../assets/my-feature/template.ejs'`
- Import SCSS: `import '../../../assets/my-feature/my-feature.scss'`
- Use `template(myTemplate)({})` to render

## Testing plugins

```ts
import { describe, it, expect, beforeEach, vi } from 'vitest'
// Mock Clappr core and browser APIs
// Test: bindEvents wiring, render output, config option handling
```

Do not test Clappr internals — only test your plugin's public behavior.
